<subSubSection id="6782CF057CB42E0BF5F4084E02802AA5" type="description">
<paragraph id="B0AEC13989D934ACE85E4627F3E7CC00" pageNumber="598">
<taxonomicName id="A9A1A2290E32F9994687B267C7003BBA" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142583" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soritis">P. soritis</taxonomicName>
is distinguished within this complex by the following combination of traits.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7E8A1D7310F5BF3911A1CA6C39A31DE3" pageNumber="598">Major: extensive transverse carinulae of occiput curve laterally and forward, with many reaching the anterior border of the head capsule; almost entire dorsal surface of head, including clypeus, carinulate; rugulae lacking on head; humerus low and smoothly convex; postpetiole seen from above laterally angulate; small denticle present on anterior ventral surface of postpetiole in side view.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB264E0D7AF7183119BBA60EDBBD86E2" pageNumber="599">Minor: dorsal profile of promesonotum lined solely with evenly spaced pairs of clavate hairs; similar hairs occur on the waist; eye very large.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="196F857C07B00F248DB666E3A3B5FA66" pageNumber="599">
The tangled infraspecific nomenclature of this species has been built mostly on variation in the sculpturing of the minor's head. From central Texas north and west, the posterior dorsal surface is foveolate and opaque (
<taxonomicName id="A9119371C74CF10BA8705072B0593D74" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:151179" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole pilifera subsp. rufescens" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole arnoldi rufescens Arnold" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pilifera" subSpecies="rufescens">subsp. rufescens</taxonomicName>
= 
<taxonomicName id="389D6ECA7AB8AB3E54488A47A1550C99" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:232344" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole pilifera subsp. campestris" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole sitarches campestris Creighton" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pilifera" subSpecies="campestris">subsp. campestris</taxonomicName>
). To the south, into Mexico, it is smooth and shiny, as illustrated here (
<taxonomicName id="C98660F952B4EE14DDD1CCE82F200746" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34013" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole pilifera subsp. sitarches" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole sitarches Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pilifera" subSpecies="sitarches">subsp. sitarches</taxonomicName>
). Westward to Arizona and Utah it is carinulate (typical 
<taxonomicName id="97DF14CBDAEC85300EDA7AAFEB7E6148" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142583" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole soritis Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soritis">soritis</taxonomicName>
). Whether this variation is truly geographic within a single species or reflects the existence of sibling species around 
<taxonomicName id="BEDC29961A1596704AACE58D53782B6B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34013" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole sitarches Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole sitarches Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sitarches">sitarches</taxonomicName>
sensu str., is a question that awaits closer field and museum research.
</paragraph>
